  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, Adaptive, Relation-Aware Fusion of Global and Local Features (ARAF), designed to dynamically integrate global property representations with local sentence features for improved document-level relation extraction. The core innovation lies in a relation-conditioned adaptive fusion module that learns to modulate the integration of global structural information (e.g., from a latent document graph) and local contextual features (e.g., from mention-level encoders) based on the semantic demands of each specific relation type. The model first constructs a global entity graph using a latent structure induction mechanism, capturing long-range dependencies and multi-hop connections across the document. Simultaneously, local features are extracted via fine-grained mention encoding, preserving syntactic and positional details within individual sentences. Crucially, we introduce a Relation-Aware Gating Unit (RAGU) that takes as input a learned meta-embedding for each relation type (derived from a relation prototype memory bank) and performs cross-attention between global and local feature sets. This unit outputs dynamic fusion weights that determine how much each representation stream contributes to the final relation score. Additionally, we incorporate an uncertainty-aware refinement loop that identifies low-confidence predictions and triggers iterative re-fusion with updated context aggregation. This allows the model to refine its focus when initial fusion proves insufficient. By making the fusion process both relation-specific and adaptive, ARAF addresses key limitations in existing methods: it avoids one-size-fits-all integration, better handles diverse reasoning patterns (local vs. global), and improves robustness in multi-relational, multi-mention settings. We evaluate ARAF on DocRED, CDR, and GDA, demonstrating consistent improvements over state-of-the-art baselines, particularly in long-distance and multi-hop relation scenarios. The framework’s modular design allows integration with various backbone encoders (e.g., BERT, RoBERTa) and graph induction strategies, enhancing its applicability across domains. This work contributes a paradigm shift—from static to semantic-aware, adaptive fusion—offering a new direction for modeling hierarchical and heterogeneous information in complex NLP tasks.",
