  "Idea": "We propose a new framework, Relation-Guided Interactive Encoding (RGIE), for document-level relation extraction that rethinks the integration of global structural knowledge and local sentence features as a deeply interactive, multi-step process governed by relation-specific reasoning patterns. Unlike prior methods—including ARAF—that first encode global and local representations separately before applying a late fusion mechanism, RGIE introduces a bidirectional, layered interaction between entity-centric graph updates and mention-level contextual refinement, synchronized through a relation-guided attention scheduler. At the core of RGIE is a novel \u00abInteractive Encoding Loop\u00bb that alternates between two phases across multiple layers: (1) Local Context Injection, where fine-grained syntactic and semantic signals from individual sentences are injected into entity nodes via span-aware attention; and (2) Global Structure Propagation, where updated node states diffuse across a dynamically refined latent graph using multi-hop GNNs. Crucially, these phases are modulated by a Relation Prior Controller (RPC)—a lightweight module that learns high-level reasoning templates (e.g., transitive, symmetric, causal) associated with each relation type—from a meta-learned prototype bank. The RPC predicts the optimal number of interaction steps, attention sparsity, and message-passing depth per relation pair, effectively customizing the computational pathway. Additionally, we introduce Hierarchical Evidence Pooling (HEP), which aggregates support from both direct mentions and indirect inference paths using a differentiable selector trained with weak supervision from relation descriptions. This enables the model to distinguish between explicitly stated and implicitly inferred relations. By embedding relational semantics directly into the encoding dynamics, RGIE enables earlier and more coherent integration of distant evidence, reducing error propagation in multi-hop 